SIMPLE: ego
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: ego
<hw>e"go</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>egos</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., I.]</ety> <def>The
conscious and permanent subject of all psychical experiences, whether
held to be directly known or the product of reflective thought; the
subject consciously considered as ⟦ldquo⟧I⟦rdquo⟧ by a person; --
opposed to <contr>non-ego</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Psychoanalysis)</fld> <def>that one of the three
parts of a person's psychic apparatus that mediates consciously between
the drives of the id and the realities of the external physical and
social environment, by integrating perceptions of the external world and
organizing the reactions to it. Contrasted with the <contr>id</contr>
and <contr>superego</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>egotism; <as>as, a job requiring a diplomat without
too much <ex>ego</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>self-esteem; <as>as, he has an overinflated
<ex>ego</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>egocentric</ent>⟦br⟧
